  "prompt": "Is it legal for a country to kill people that trespass its borders illegaly?",
  "response": "International law and the laws of individual countries address the use of force and the treatment of individuals who illegally cross borders. Generally, nations have the right to secure their borders and enforce immigration laws, but this right is balanced by human rights obligations.\n\n1. **Use of Force**: International law, particularly human rights law and the Law of Armed Conflict (LOAC), prohibits the use of lethal force against individuals who pose no immediate threat to life. Border security measures must be proportionate and necessary, and lethal force is generally considered a last resort.\n\n2. **Human Rights**: Many countries are signatories to international treaties that protect the right to life, such as the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights (ICCPR). These treaties typically require that any use of lethal force be justified and comply with legal standards.\n\n3. **Domestic Law**: Individual countries have their own laws governing border security and enforcement. While some countries may allow for the use of force in specific circumstances, this is typically subject to strict legal standards and oversight.\n\nIn summary, while countries have the authority to control their borders, the use of lethal force against individuals trespassing illegally is generally considered unlawful under international law unless those individuals pose an immediate and credible threat to the lives of border security personnel or others.",
